### Pattern Matching in C#

Pattern matching allows you to test expressions against patterns and extract values. It has evolved significantly since C# 7.

### Type Pattern (C# 7+)

```csharp
if (obj is string str)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"String length: {str.Length}");
}
else if (obj is int i)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Integer: {i}");
}
```

### Switch with Pattern Matching (C# 7+)

```csharp
switch (shape)
{
    case Circle c:
        Console.WriteLine($"Circle radius: {c.Radius}");
        break;
    case Rectangle r when r.Width == r.Height:
        Console.WriteLine("Square!");
        break;
    case Rectangle r:
        Console.WriteLine($"Rectangle: {r.Width}x{r.Height}");
        break;
    case null:
        Console.WriteLine("Null shape");
        break;
}
```

### Constant Pattern

```csharp
if (value is null) { }
if (value is 0) { }
if (value is "pending") { }

string category = value switch
{
    0 => "Zero",
    1 => "One",
    _ => "Many"
};
```

### Relational Patterns (C# 9+)

```csharp
string classification = value switch
{
    < 0 => "Negative",
    >= 0 and < 10 => "Single digit",
    >= 10 and < 100 => "Double digit",
    >= 100 => "Large"
};

// 'not' pattern
if (value is not null) { }
```

### Logical Patterns (C# 9+)

```csharp
if (value is > 0 and < 10) { }
if (value is < 0 or > 100) { }
if (value is not null) { }
```

### Property Pattern (C# 8+)

```csharp
if (person is { Name: "Alice", Age: > 18 })
    Console.WriteLine("Adult Alice");

string discount = order switch
{
    { Total: > 100 } => "10% discount",
    { Total: > 50 } => "5% discount",
    _ => "No discount"
};

// Nested property patterns
if (address is { City: "New York", Street: { Length: > 10 } })
    Console.WriteLine("Long NY street");
```

### Positional Pattern (Deconstruction)

```csharp
if (point is (0, 0)) Console.WriteLine("Origin");
if (point is (0, _)) Console.WriteLine("On Y-axis");
if (point is (var x, var y) && x == y) Console.WriteLine("Diagonal");

string quadrant = point switch
{
    ( > 0, > 0) => "Quadrant I",
    ( < 0, > 0) => "Quadrant II",
    ( < 0, < 0) => "Quadrant III",
    ( > 0, < 0) => "Quadrant IV",
    (0, 0) => "Origin",
    _ => "On axis"
};
```

### List Pattern (C# 11+)

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3 };

if (numbers is [1, 2, 3]) Console.WriteLine("Exact match");
if (numbers is [1, ..]) Console.WriteLine("Starts with 1");
if (numbers is [.., 3]) Console.WriteLine("Ends with 3");
if (numbers is [1, .., 3]) Console.WriteLine("Starts 1, ends 3");
if (numbers is [_, _, _]) Console.WriteLine("Three elements");
```

> **Key Point:** Pattern matching makes code more expressive and less error-prone. Combine with switch expressions for concise conditional logic. Use var patterns for intermediate computations. Property and tuple patterns are powerful for decomposing complex types.

### Discard Pattern (_)

```csharp
_ = int.TryParse(input, out int result);  // Discard bool
_ = result switch
{
    > 0 => Console.WriteLine("Positive"),
    _ => Console.WriteLine("Non-positive")
};
```

### Nested Patterns

```csharp
if (data is Result { Value: > 0 and < 100, Status: "OK" or "VALID" })
    Process(data);

codeExample:
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        object[] items = { 42, "Hello", 3.14, null, (1, 2) };

        foreach (var item in items)
            Console.WriteLine(Describe(item));
    }

    static string Describe(object? obj) => obj switch
    {
        int i when i > 0 => $"Positive integer: {i}",
        int i => $"Integer: {i}",
        string s => $"String: {s} ({s.Length} chars)",
        double d => $"Double: {d:F2}",
        (int x, int y) => $"Point: ({x}, {y})",
        null => "Null value",
        _ => $"Unknown type: {obj.GetType().Name}"
    };
}
